Face2Age

Predicting a person's age (work-in-progress)

Nov 15, 2020 • Jesse van Elteren • 1 min read

The MAE of the model on the validation dataset is 4.3. Below you see how the predictions and actuals more or less match

The error gets larger as someone gets older, which makes perfect sense. If you see a baby you are not going to guess wrong by more then 5 years, but for someone age 60 that is way more difficult. The error fluctuates a bit, which is due to some imbalance in the dataset (there are few images of really old people).

Text(0.5, 0, 'Actual age')
<!DOCTYPE svg PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD SVG 1.1//EN" "http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/1.1/DTD/svg11.dtd">

I’ve also build a webpage where you can try out if you can beat the computer, or even upload a selfie to see the results. I’ve taken some selfies and the computer estimated me around 27 to 42, which is ballpark accurate. But an condolence card of my grandmother age 92 was classified as 62. She did look young, but 62 was a bit of an underestimation…

That’s it, I’ve had much fun with this project. I hope you’ve liked it as well and will try out the app. Click here to see if we collectively can outperform the computer.

Note: Some technical details on how it was build: Pytorch, Pretrained resnet-18 model. Application runs on Google Cloud Platform, with a Nginx and Gunicorn running in Docker container. Python backend in Fastapi.
